### <a id="best-practices"></a> Best Practices

This section describes best practices for backing up your <%= vars.platform_name %> deployment.

#### <a id="backup-frequency"></a> Frequency of Backups

<%= vars.recommended_by %> recommends that you take backups in proportion to the rate of change of the data in <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %> to minimize the number of changes lost if a restore is required. <%= vars.recommended_by %> recommends starting with backing up every 24 hours. If app developers make frequent changes, you should increase the frequency of backups.

#### <a id="artifact-retention"></a> Retention of Backup Artifacts

Operators should retain backup artifacts based on the timeframe they need to be able to restore to. For example, if backups are taken every 24 hours and <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %> must be able to be restored to three days prior, three sets of backup artifacts should be retained.

Artifacts should be stored in two data centers other than the <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %> data center. When deciding the restore timeframe, you should take other factors such as compliance and audit-ability into account.

#### <a id="security"></a> Security

<%= vars.recommended_by %> recommends that you encrypt artifacts and store them securely.


## <a id="recreation"></a> Disaster Recovery by Re-Creating the Deployment

An alternative strategy for recovering <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %> after a disaster is to have automation in place so that all the data can be re-created. This requires that every modification to <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %> settings and state is automated, typically through the use of a pipeline.

Recovery steps include creating a new <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %>, re-creating orgs, spaces, users, services, service bindings and other state, and re-pushing apps.

For more information about this approach, see the Cloud Foundry Summit presentation [Multi-DC Cloud Foundry: What, Why and How?](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t61r8THmtsc) on YouTube.


## <a id="different-topologies"></a> Disaster Recovery for Different Topologies

This section describes disaster recovery strategies for different <%= vars.platform_name %> deployment topologies.

### <a id="active-active"></a> Active-Active

To prevent app downtime, some Pivotal customers run an active-active deployment, where they run two or more identical <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %> deployments in different data centers. If one <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %> deployment becomes unavailable, traffic is seamlessly routed to the other deployment. To achieve identical deployments, all operations to <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %> are automated so they can be applied to both <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %> deployments in parallel.

Because all operations have been automated, the automation approach to disaster recovery is a viable option for an active-active deployment. Disaster recovery requires re-creating <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %>, then running all the automation to re-create state.

This option requires discipline to automate all changes to <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %>. Some of the operations that need to be automated are:

* App push, restage, scale
* Org, space, and user create, read, update, and delete (CRUD)
* Service instance CRUD
* Service bindings CRUD
* Routes CRUD
* Security groups CRUD
* Quota CRUD

Human-initiated changes always make their way into the system. These changes can include quotas being raised, new settings being enabled, and incident responses. For this reason, <%= vars.recommended_by %> recommends taking backups even when using an automated disaster recovery strategy.

